Note: The RLS policy on extension_requests allows DELETE only for admins. We need to also allow the requester to delete their own pending request. However, since we can't modify the DB schema in this task, use an UPDATE approach instead — set status to 'cancelled':

Actually, the status CHECK constraint only allows 'pending', 'accepted', 'rejected'. So we can't add 'cancelled' without a migration. 

**Simplest approach: use 'rejected' status** — when the requester cancels, mark it as rejected (self-rejected). This works within the existing schema constraints.

```dart
/// Cancels a pending extension request by marking it as rejected.
///
/// Used when the requester wants to withdraw their own request before
/// the next user responds.
Future<void> cancelExtensionRequest(String requestId) async {
  final now = DateTime.now().toIso8601String();
  await SupabaseConfig.client
      .from('extension_requests')
      .update({'status': 'rejected', 'resolved_at': now})
      .eq('id', requestId)
      .eq('status', 'pending');
}
```

### 2. getAcceptedRequestsForRequester(String userId)
Returns all accepted extension requests where the given user was the requester. Used to check the per-cycle limit.

```dart
/// Returns all accepted extension requests where [userId] is the requester,
/// ordered by creation time (newest first).
///
/// Used to enforce the per-cycle prórroga limit.
Future<List<ExtensionRequest>> getAcceptedRequestsForRequester(
  String userId,
) async {
  final data = await SupabaseConfig.client
      .from('extension_requests')
      .select()
      .eq('requester_id', userId)
      .eq('status', 'accepted')
      .order('created_at', ascending: false);
  return data.map((json) => ExtensionRequest.fromJson(json)).toList();
}
```

